snippet.textDisplay:
Brandon Boyd was interviewed about 10 years ago on a radio show I listened to in Florida.

They talked about artists losing inspiration and taking the easy route making unoriginal songs with repetitive lyrics and repetitive song progressions , the entirety of songs artists make after they lose creativity are a downward trend towards repetitiveness.

You could skip any part of the song track and no matter where you’re at in the song it’s no different.

That’s how I feel about Ozzy. I have respect for him , but I won’t listen to a lot of this repetitive stuff. There’s no progression, it’s like being on a rollercoaster that’s going on a straight linear track in a circle loop.
snippet.textOriginal:
Brandon Boyd was interviewed about 10 years ago on a radio show I listened to in Florida.  

They talked about artists losing inspiration and taking the easy route making unoriginal songs with repetitive lyrics and repetitive song progressions , the entirety of songs artists make after they lose creativity are a downward trend towards repetitiveness. 

You could skip any part of the song track and no matter where you’re at in the song it’s no different. 

That’s how I feel about Ozzy.  I have respect for him , but I won’t listen to a lot of this repetitive stuff.  There’s no progression, it’s like being on a rollercoaster that’s going on a straight linear track in a circle loop.
